component.pre-assembly-instructions:
Note: If your robot has left- and right-side motors (the typical case), you should attach the red wire to the top tab of one motor and the bottom tab of the other (and vice versa for the black wire).

  1. Attach a motor bracket to each of the motors using the bracket mounting screws.
  2. It should be oriented so the mounting plate (i.e., the portion of the bracket that is not attached to the motor), is next to the black wire.
  3. Cut the red and black hookup wires in half.
  4. Strip 1.5mm of the cut ends.
  5. Twist the exposed ends of the wires to form tight bundles.
  6. Thread one end of the red wire through the hole in the copper tab on the top of the motor.
  7. Bend the tip of the wire back on itself, securing the wire to the copper tab./li>
  8. Apply some solder to hold wire in place.
  9. Apply a blob of hot glue to around the tab and the solder joint to re-enforce the connection.
  10. Repeat the process for the black wire and the other tab.
component.board-assembly-instructions:
1. Find the location for this part on your PCB by matching up the outline and name.
  2. Use hot glue to attach the motors to the PCB or use the mounting screws and nuts to attach the motor to the PCB.
  3. Solder the 2-pin female header in place on the board.
  4. Insert the tips of the wires into the header matching the wire color with the label or the board.

  2. Place the right-angle female headers into the holes (be sure to orient them so that they fit with in the outline on the PCB. Solder them in place from the underside of your robot's PCB.
component.post-assembly-instructions: 1. Insert the pins on the Raspberry Pi into the holes in the right-angle female header.
